The paper focuses on developing a system for fine-grained indoor location-based social networking, which involves the use of crowd-sensed data, algorithms for detecting fake check-ins, and enhancing system performance based on user feedback. This work is highly relevant to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), as it deals with the development of a social network based on location data. Additionally, the paper discusses the user experience and the use of mobile devices, which suggests a connection to the sub-category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC). The use of semantic fingerprints and algorithms for detecting new places and predicting names of new venues suggests a connection to Multimedia (cs.MM), Information Retrieval (cs.IR), and Databases (cs.DB) sub-categories.
